INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (144,1,'2014-03-19 14:43:33','2014-03-19 14:43:33','<a href=\"http://myvaccinelawyer.com/aboutheprogram.html\">The Vaccine Injury Compensation Program (VICP)</a> was created to compensate persons suffering from serious injury or illness related to a vaccine.  Therefore, the Act includes a provision that, in order to receive compensation, an injured party must have symptoms lasting for six months.  The purpose of the provision is to ensure that only serious reactions/injuries are compensated.  Although the requirement is an arbitrary one (a person suffering for five months is not to be compensated, yet one suffering for six months is?), it is the rule.   However, any residual symptoms will suffice.  The symptoms need not be as severe as they were in month one, nor must they be of any particular severity – they simply must exist after six months to any degree.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nHowever, the Act neglected to take into account situations where a petitioner does have a serious, even potentially life-threatening condition that was corrected by surgery.  Therefore, in 2000, the Act was amended to include compensation for persons who required “inpatient hospitalization and surgical intervention.”  Surgical intervention is not defined within the Act.  The provision was added with a particular purpose in mind – to compensate those injured by the <a href=\"http://myvaccinelawyer.com/harmfulvaccines/rotavirus.html\">rotavirus vaccine</a> who did not otherwise meet the Act’s six month requirement.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://myvaccinelawyer.com/blog/rotavirus-can-cause-stomach-blockage-infants/\">The rotavirus vaccine can cause intussusception</a>, which is a condition characterized by the “telescoping” of the intestine.  The reaction can occur quickly after vaccination.  The intestine prolapses into an adjoining section of intestine, like a smaller telescope section retracting into a larger section of the scope.  Intussusception is extremely painful and could result in sudden and potentially fatal complications.\r\n\r\nThe treatment for intussusception often involves surgery.  A successful surgery can resolve the condition relatively quickly with little to no lasting effects.  Therefore, although a child and his/her parents may have suffered immensely during the period of illness, the injury will not involve symptoms lasting six months.  Congress recognized the injustice in such a bar on recovery, so the Act was amended.\r\n\r\nWhat constitutes “surgical intervention” under the Act?  That remains to be seen as the case law further develops.   Some procedures have been tested already; therefore we know the following procedures <i>are not </i>considered surgical intervention by the Vaccine Court:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Blood transfusions</li>\r\n	<li>Intravenous (IV) drugs/fluids</li>\r\n	<li>Lumbar punctures (spinal taps)</li>\r\n	<li>Barium enema with inpatient hospitalization (for Intussusception)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nHopefully, petitioners will continue to press the issue to create precedent.  In cases where a surgical procedure allowed an injured person to recover faster than the six months, we will certainly fight to have the procedure included under the “surgical intervention” umbrella.\r\n\r\nOur attorneys have dedicated their careers to fighting for the victims of severe reactions to vaccines.  We currently represent clients across the country that have undergone various surgical procedures as a result of vaccine injuries.  If you believe you may have suffered an adverse reaction to a vaccine, please <a href=\"http://www.myvaccinelawyer.com/contactus.html\">contact My Vaccine Lawyer</a> at (800) 229-7704 for a free consultation.','Vaccine Injury Compensation Program – Exception to Rule Requiring Six Months of Symptoms','','publish','closed','open','','vaccine-injury-compensation-program-exception-symptoms-six-months-rule','','\nhttp://myvaccinelawyer.com/blog/rotavirus-can-cause-stomach-blockage-infants/','2014-05-15 14:25:49','2014-05-15 14:25:49','',0,'http://myvaccinelawyer.com/blog/?p=144',0,'post','',0);
