INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (147,1,'2014-04-09 15:35:29','2014-04-09 15:35:29','<i>If you or a loved one believe you have suffered a reaction to a vaccination, it is imperative that you not only see your medical professional immediately, but be as descriptive and thorough as possible during your visits.</i>\r\n\r\nMedical Records are absolutely crucial to the litigation of a vaccine case.  The information contained within medical records is fundamental to proving that an individual received a vaccination and suffered a reaction or injury that was caused by the vaccination. Not only is the Petitioner required to submit all of the vaccination records and treatment records, they must also provide complete medical records for three years prior to the vaccination. Once the records are submitted, the Department of Health and Human Services performs an extensive records review to form an opinion as to whether the Petitioner should be entitled to compensation through the program.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nIn <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Arthur Cline v. Sec’y of Health &amp; Human Servs.,</span> the U.S. Court of Federal Claims discussed the role of medical records in a vaccine case:\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">“The process for finding facts in the Vaccine Program begins with analyzing the medical records, which are required to be filed with the petition. Medical records that are created contemporaneously with the events that they describe are presumed to be not only accurate, but complete. Completeness is presumed due to a series of propositions. First, when people are ill, they see a medical professional. Second, when ill people see a doctor, they report all of their problems to the doctor. Third, having heard about the symptoms, the doctor records what they were told.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The presumption that contemporaneously created medical records are accurate and complete is rebuttable. For cases alleging a condition found in the Vaccine Injury Table, special masters may find when a first symptom appeared, despite the lack of a notation in a contemporaneous medical record. In such cases, special masters are expected to consider whether medical records are accurate and complete.”</p>\r\nFor this reason, it is imperative that individuals who believe they suffered a reaction to a vaccine must be as descriptive and thorough as possible with their medical professionals.  Doctors can only record what they are told, and for the purposes of the vaccine injury compensation program, courts presume medical records to be complete and accurate (although that presumption <i>can </i>be overcome with additional evidence and/or testimony). Therefore, potential vaccine injury victims must provide as much information to doctors as possible to ensure a comprehensive medical record and a fair evaluation of their case. Frankly, it can mean the difference between winning and losing.\r\n\r\nIf you or a loved one has suffered a reaction or injury after a vaccination, visit our website at <a href=\"http://www.myvaccinelawyer.com/\">www.myvaccinelawyer.com</a> and contact one of our national vaccine attorneys as soon as possible.  We can ensure you take the necessary steps to protect your legal rights in the event of a potential claim.','The Significance of Medical Records in Winning Your Vaccine Case','','publish','closed','open','','significance-medical-records-winning-vaccine-case','','','2014-04-14 00:20:16','2014-04-14 00:20:16','',0,'http://myvaccinelawyer.com/blog/?p=147',0,'post','',0);
