d could result in sudden and potentially fatal complications.\r\n\r\nThe treatment for intussusception often involves surgery.  A successful surgery can resolve the condition relatively quickly with little to no lasting effects.  Therefore, although a child and his/her parents may have suffered immensely during the period of illness, the injury will not involve symptoms lasting six months.  Congress recognized the injustice in such a bar on recovery, so the Act was amended.\r\n\r\nWhat constitutes “surgical intervention” under the Act?  That remains to be seen as the case law further develops.   Some procedures have been tested already; therefore we know the following procedures <i>are not </i>considered surgical intervention by the Vaccine Court:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Blood transfusions</li>\r\n	<li>Intravenous (IV) drugs/fluids</li>\r\n	<li>Lumbar punctures (spinal taps)</li>\r\n	<li>Barium enema with inpatient hospitalization (for Intussusception)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nHopefully, petitioners will continue to press the issue to create precedent.  In cases where a surgical procedure allowed an injured person to recover faster than the six months, we will certainly fight to have the procedure included under the “surgical intervention” umbrella.\r\n\r\nOur attorneys have dedicated their careers to fighting for the victims of severe reactions to vaccines.  We currently represent clients across the country that have undergone various surgical procedures as a result of vaccine injuries.  If you believe you may have suffered an adverse reaction to a vaccine, please <a href=\"http://www.myvaccinelawyer.com/contactus.html\">contact My Vaccine Lawyer</a> at (800) 229-7704 for a free consultation.','Vaccine Injury Compensation Program – Exception to Rule Requiring Six Months of Symptoms','','inherit','closed','open','','144-revision-v1','','','2014-05-15 14:25:49','2014-05-15 14:25:49','',144,'http://myvaccinelawyer.com/blog/144-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (156,1,'2014-09-04 01:58:38','2014-09-04 01:58:38','The US Food and Drug Administration has ordered<span class=\"apple-converted-space\"> </span>GlaxoSmithKline<span class=\"apple-converted-space\"> (“GSK”) </span>to review its manufacturing operations after finding a Canadian subsidiary violated quality requirements during the manufacture of its flu vaccine FluLaval.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nIn a warning letter<span class=\"apple-converted-space\"> </span>to the British company, the FDA cited \"deviations from current good manufacturing practice\" in the manufacture of FluLaval at GSK\'s Quebec-based subsidiary ID Biomedical, which makes the vaccine for Canada and the US.\r\n\r\nDuring inspections in April, the FDA found that the plant had failed to take appropriate steps to prevent microbiological contamination of drug products purporting to be sterile. It also found that controls for the purified water system at the sitewere inadequate to prevent contamination.\r\n\r\nThe FDA stated it \"expects ID Biomedical and GSK to undertake a comprehensive and global assessment of all of its manufacturing operations to ensure that all products conform to FDA requirements\".\r\n\r\nGSK stated \"patient safety is our first priority and we are confident in the safety of the influenza vaccines we have provided to patients. Every batch of GSK vaccines is subject to extensive review before it is released. Vaccines that do not pass this rigorous review are discarded.\"\r\n\r\nPending FDA approvals, GSK now expects to provide between 28m and 33m doses of flu vaccine to the US health authorities for next winter. It had planned to supply 36m doses, 23m of which would be made in the Sainte-Foy site in Quebec. GSK is also working with the Canadian health authorities to meet its supply commitments for 2014-15.\r\n\r\nVaccines are one of GSK\'s key growth areas.','FDA Orders Flu Vaccine Manufacturer to Evaluate Contamination Issues','','publish','closed','open','','fda-orders-flu-vaccine-manufacturer-evaluate-contamination-issues','','','2014-09-04 01:58:55','2014-09-04 01:58:55','',0,'http://myvaccinelawyer.com/blog/?p=156',0,'post','',0);
